  <div class="doctitle">US Government Export-Control Suspension of Anthropic's Fable&nbsp;5&nbsp;/&nbsp;Mythos&nbsp;5</div>
  <div class="docmeta"><b>Topic:</b> AI &amp; Machine Learning &nbsp;·&nbsp; <b>Basis:</b> primary source + balanced multi-region corroboration via Aunoo</div>
  <div class="audience">FOR AUNOO CLIENTS</div>

  <div class="bluf">
    <div class="h">Bottom line up front</div>
    On <b>Friday, 12 June 2026 (directive timestamped 5:21&nbsp;p.m.&nbsp;ET)</b>, the US Commerce Department, citing national-security authorities, ordered Anthropic to suspend all access to its Fable&nbsp;5 and Mythos&nbsp;5 models for any foreign national worldwide, including Anthropic's own foreign-born employees. Unable to cleanly partition access, Anthropic disabled both models for every customer, US citizens included. All other Claude models remain available. This is the <b>first US export-control action aimed at a specific AI model rather than chips or hardware</b>. A jailbreak of Fable&nbsp;5 had been publicly demonstrated by an independent red-teamer the day before; the government cited a jailbreak but released no specifics, so the link is reported sequence, not confirmed cause. Anthropic calls the order a "misunderstanding" and disputes the severity of the flaw.
  </div>

  <div style="background:#eef4ff;border-left:4px solid #2563eb;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;padding:9px 13px;margin:0 0 14px;font-size:8.7pt">
    <b style="color:#1e40af">Latest — 14 Jun:</b> Anthropic has sent senior technical staff to Washington and held virtual meetings with White House officials since Friday to resolve the dispute; both sides say they want a resolution (Axios, single-source). This points toward restoration rather than escalation.
  </div>

  <h2 class="sec">What happened</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Anthropic released <b>Fable&nbsp;5</b> (public) and <b>Mythos&nbsp;5</b> (trusted partners only) on <b>Tuesday, 9 June 2026</b>. The two are the same underlying model split by safety classifiers; on high-risk queries Fable&nbsp;5 hands off to a weaker model. Anthropic said pre-launch that testing found no universal jailbreaks.</li>
    <li><b>The jailbreak was demonstrated publicly, before the order.</b> On 10–11 June, red-teamer "Pliny the Liberator" bypassed Fable&nbsp;5's classifiers, published working x86 stack-exploit and chemical-synthesis output, and leaked the model's ~120,000-character system prompt.</li>
    <li><b>Cause: cited, not confirmed.</b> The government cited a "jailbreak" but gave no specifics and did not name the public demonstration, so the link is inferred. The Wall Street Journal separately reports the trigger was talks between Amazon's CEO and US officials.</li>
    <li><b>Net effect:</b> an abrupt, global blackout of both models. Domestic US users lost access as collateral, since compliance required a full shutdown.</li>
  </ul>

